 <!-- ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ -->
 <!--  Introduction -->
 <!-- ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ -->
 <purpose>
   <p>
     This part of ISO 10303 specifies an application module 
     for the representation of a class or set. A
     class or set may be:
   </p>

   <dl>
     <dt>class by extension</dt>
     <dd>a class that is defined by specifying a criterion for membership,
     which does not enumerate the members</dd>

     <dt>class by intension</dt>
     <dd>a class that is defined by enumerating its members.</dd>
   </dl>

   <note>
     This module can be used in combination with another
     module, such as 
     <module_ref linkend="product_view_definition:introduction">
       Product view definition
     </module_ref>,
     in order to indicate that
     a Product view definition is a 
     
     <express_ref linkend="class:arm:class_arm.Class"/>.
     In the ARM of the combined module, an application object is created,
     which is both a        
     <express_ref
       linkend="Product_view_definition_arm:arm:Product_view_definition_arm.Product_view_definition"/> 
     and a <b>Class</b>. This
     application object inherits from <b>Class</b> the following
     capabilities: 
 <ul>
   <li> 
   involvement in set theory relationships, such as union and
   intersection;  
 </li>
 <li>
   specification an individual member by a classification
   relationship; and  
 </li>
 <li>enumeration of the complete membership.</li>
</ul>
   </note>
 </purpose>

  <!-- ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ -->
 <!--  In scope statement -->
 <!-- ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ -->
 <inscope>
   <li>the existence of a class or set;</li>
   <li>
     the distinction between a class or set that is defined by abstract
     criteria, and a class or set that is defined by enumerating its
     members.
   </li> 
 </inscope>

 <!-- ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ -->
 <!--  Out of scope statement -->
 <!-- ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ -->
 <outscope>
   <li>classification and the specification of complete set membership;</li>
   <li>set theory relationships;
   <note>
     Set theory relationships are within the scope of the
     <module_ref linkend="set_theory:introduction">set_theory</module_ref> application
     module. 
   </note>
 </li>
 <li>mappings between sets or classes;</li>
 <li>relationships that are not set theory relationships.</li>
 </outscope>

